The '''Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation''' ('''IHME''') is a research institute working in the area of [[global health]] statistics and impact evaluation at the [[University of Washington]] in Seattle. The Institute is headed by Dr. [[Christopher J.L. Murray]], a physician and health economist, and professor at the [[University of Washington Department of Global Health]], which is part of the [[School of Medicine]]. IHME's goal, as stated on the Institute's website, is "to identify the best strategies to build a healthier world. By measuring health, tracking program performance, finding ways to maximize health system impact, and developing innovative measurement systems, IHME provides a foundation for informed decision-making that ultimately will lead to better health globally" IHME (2011).<ref>{{cite web|title=Institute for Heath Metrics and Evaluation|url=http://www.healthmetricsandevaluation.org/research|accessdate=27 June 2011}}</ref>  IHME conducts research and trains scientists, policymakers, and the public in health metrics concepts, methods, and tools. Its mission includes judging the effectiveness and efficacy of health initiatives and national health systems. IHME's work seeks to be complementary to the [[United Nations]]' work in the [[World Health Organization]] in that it shares many tasks but is independent from member countries.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNiel|first1=Donal|title=Gates Foundation's Influence Criticized|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/16/science/16malaria.html?_r=0|accessdate=9 May 2010|publisher=New York Times|date=16 February 2008}}</ref><ref name="2008_doughton">{{cite news|last1=Doughton|first1=Sandi|title=Seattle institute aims to help cure world-health data disorder|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/seattle-institute-aims-to-help-cure-world-health-data-disorder/|accessdate=9 May 2010|publisher=Seattle Times|date=9 April 2008}}</ref>

IHME gathers health-related data from all available sources. It develops innovative analytical tools to track trends in mortality, diseases, and risk factors, and capsulizes many of its research findings in data visualizations.<ref>{{cite web|title=Data Visualizations|url=http://www.healthdata.org/results/data-visualizations|website=Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation|accessdate=27 February 2015}}</ref>  It evaluates interventions such as vaccines, malaria control policies, cancer screenings, and birth care. To enable researchers to replicate IHME's work and to foster new research, IHME created the Global Health Data Exchange (GHDx) where methods and results are cataloged and freely accessible. IHME is also committed to expanding the field of health metrics by training students at the post-baccalaureate and post-graduate levels.

==History==

IHME was launched in June 2007 based on a core grant of $105 million primarily funded by the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Paulson|first1=Tom|title=$105 million Gates gift helps start global health center|url=http://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/105-million-Gates-gift-helps-start-global-1239473.php|accessdate=9 May 2010|publisher=Seattle PI|date=4 June 2007}}</ref> Among its earliest projects was to produce new estimates of mortality rates, which were published in ''The Lancet'' in September 2007.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Murray|first1=CJL|last2=Laakso|first2=T|last3=Shibuya|first3=K|last4=Lopez|first4=AD|title=Can we achieve Millennium Development Goal 4? New analysis of country trends and forecasts of under-5 mortality to 2015|journal=The Lancet|date=22 September 2007|volume=370|pages=1040–1054|url=http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140673607614780/abstract|accessdate=27 February 2015|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(07)61478-0}}</ref> The Institute updated these in 2010<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rajaratnam|first1=JK|last2=Marcus|first2=JR|last3=Flaxman|first3=AD|last4=Wang|first4=H|last5=Levin-Rector|first5=A|last6=Dwyer|first6=L|last7=Costa|first7=M|last8=Lopez|first8=AD|last9=Murray|first9=CJL|title=Neonatal, postneonatal, childhood, and under-5 mortality for 187 countries, 1970–2010: a systematic analysis of progress towards Millennium Development Goal 4|journal=The Lancet|date=24 May 2010|volume=375|pages=1988–2008|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(10)60703-9}}</ref>
and again in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global, regional, and national levels of neonatal, infant, and under-5 mortality during 1990–2013: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2013|url=http://download.thelancet.com/flatcontentassets/pdfs/S0140673614606966.pdf|publisher=''[[The Lancet]]''|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> Maternal,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hogan|first1=MC|last2=Foreman|first2=KJ|last3=Naghavi|first3=M|last4=Ahn|first4=SY|last5=Wang|first5=M|last6=Makela|first6=SM|last7=Lopez|first7=AD|last8=Lozano|first8=R|last9=Murray|first9=CJL|title=Maternal mortality for 181 countries, 1980-2008: a systematic analysis of progress towards Millennium Development Goal 5|journal=The Lancet|date=8 May 2010|volume=375|pages=1609–1623|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(10)60518-1}}</ref> child, and adult mortality<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rajaratnam|first1=JK|last2=Marcus|first2=JR|last3=Levin-Rector|first3=A|last4=Chalupka|first4=AN|last5=Wang|first5=H|last6=Dwyer|first6=L|last7=Costa|first7=M|last8=Lopez|first8=AD|last9=Murray|first9=CJL|title=Worldwide mortality in men and women aged 15–59 years from 1970 to 2010: a systematic analysis|journal=The Lancet|date=30 April 2010|volume=375|pages=1704–1720|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(10)60517-x|pmid=20434763}}</ref> estimates have been published, as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global, regional, and national levels and causes of maternal mortality during 1990–2013: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2013|url=http://www.healthdata.org/research-article/global-regional-and-national-levels-and-causes-maternal-mortality-during-1990%E2%80%932013|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Global, regional, and national levels and causes of maternal mortality during 1990–2013: a systematic analysis for the Global Burden of Disease Study 2013|url=http://download.thelancet.com/flatcontentassets/pdfs/S0140673614604979.pdf}}</ref>
